body:
Comparing an explicitly typed None gives a different (less helpful) diagnostic then an implicitly typed None of the same type. 

Given the following code: https://play.rust-lang.org/?version=nightly&mode=debug&edition=2018&gist=48fa4d543c6d8eec51a2c2e951828039

```rust
#[derive(Debug, Clone, Copy)]
enum Player {
    Black,
    White
}

#[derive(Debug)]
struct TTT {
    board: [[Option<Player>; 3]; 3], // 3x3 matrix
}

impl TTT {
    fn new() -> TTT {
        TTT {
            board: [[None; 3]; 3],
        }
    }
}

fn main() {
    let row = "0".parse::<usize>().unwrap();
    let game = TTT::new();
    println!("{:?}", game.board[row][0]);
    if None == game.board[row][0] {
        println!("None");
    }
    if None::<Player> == game.board[row][0] {
        println!("None");
    }
}
```

The current output is:

```
error[E0277]: can't compare `Player` with `Player`
  --> src/main.rs:26:13
   |
26 |     if None == game.board[row][0] {
   |             ^^ no implementation for `Player == Player`
   |
   = help: the trait `PartialEq` is not implemented for `Player`
   = note: required because of the requirements on the impl of `PartialEq` for `Option<Player>`

error[E0369]: binary operation `==` cannot be applied to type `Option<Player>`
  --> src/main.rs:29:23
   |
29 |     if None::<Player> == game.board[row][0] {
   |        -------------- ^^ ------------------ Option<Player>
   |        |
   |        Option<Player>
```

Ideally the output should look the same for both versions.
